Merge pull request #103 from OneGet/wip

Merge recent changes back into master.
fixed case where failed wildcard searches still proceed to install
enabled responsiveness timeout and task cancellation and aborting.

parallel calls to package providers now will not cancel the whole request if an error/exception is reported from one of them
this also means that parallel calls return warnings where errors were previously exposed
this enabled us to eliminate the extra threading in the client code where IAsyncEnumerables were being handled in their own threads
this also had a surprisingly significant performance boost
AsyncCmdlets now issue a Cancel on a PipelineStoppedException
Write* in AsyncCmdlets now check to see if the call is cancelled before attempting to perform the write
replaced my BlockingEnumerable with a new implementation that inherits the framework BlockingEnumerable. Turns out they're only a *bit* crazy.
Our GetBlockingEnumerable() is (a) ReEnumerable (ie, caching) (b) won't throw when cancelled, simply ends.
Our BlockingEnumerable is by default, blocking (instead of the Consuming, but not blocking behavior of the Framework class. That's just weird)
ReEnumerable simple ends when the underlying collection throws during MoveNext()
Consolodated the code to pass in a custom IHostApi object into the HostApiExtensions
DynamicPowerShell: Added support to to explicity support ImportModule and TestModulePath and GetCommand so we can skip the dynamic usage in the core itself.
DynamicPowerShell: LookupCommand only lists imported cmdlets/aliases/functions now (was causing crashes when some modules forced some assembly loading)
DynamicPowerShell: this does mean that modules must be explciity imported
PowerShellMetaProvider: removed excessive debug messages
PowerShellMetaProvider: streamlined provider module scanning.
PowerShellMetaProvider: excluded OneGet and OneGet-Edge modules from provider scan. (this was sometimes causing a condition where it would try to load a different version of the module)
added the blacklisted module exclusion earlier in the scanning (saves significant processing during startup)
changes the cancellation check to ask the IHostProvider on every call too; the cancellation token doesn't get tripped when one provider is cancelled in a parallel call
Added code to IAsyncEnumerable to check if the enumerable has data before enumerating it.
Added code to IAsyncEnumerable to get be able to GetConsumingEnumerable() and GetBlockingEnumerable() (*my* GetBlockingEnumerable )
DynamicType now hosts a single dynamic assembly (when not in deep-debug mode)
AsyncCmdlet's AsyncRun collapsed the three tasks into one; also employs a unhandled exception trap to discover rogue exceptions
